             <div class="txtNew" data-packed="true" id="comp-jihjhzy2" style="top:770px;bottom:;left:628px;right:;width:310px;height:auto;position:absolute;margin-left:calc((100% - 980px) * 0.5)">
              <p class="font_8" style="font-size:16px;">
               <span style="font-size:16px;">
                <span style="font-family:avenir-lt-w01_35-light1475496,sans-serif;">
                 <span class="color_14">
                  Press Release –  June 16, 2018
                 </span>
                </span>
               </span>
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
               <span class="color_14">
                <span style="font-family:raleway,sans-serif;">
                 <span style="font-size:24px;">
                  L92 - Missing Southern Resident killer whale is presumed dead
                 </span>
                </span>
               </span>
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
               On Monday, June 11, more than 50 Southern Resident killer whales returned to inland waters, including J pod, L87, and most but not all of L pod. It has been nearly 2 months since J pod whales and L87 have been seen in local waters, an unusually long break but not unexpected based on trends in the past decade. In recent years, encounter data and sighting data compiled by the Center for Research show that the Southern Residents have been spending fewer days in inland waters in the April-May time frame. This trend parallels a decline in the abundance of the Fraser River spring Chinook salmon runs.
              </p>
             </div>

               <div class="txtNew" data-packed="true" id="comp-jgslpoqk" style="top:7px;bottom:;left:440px;right:;width:470px;height:auto;position:absolute">
                <p class="font_7">
                 <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                  Where can we find an extra million twenty pound Chinook salmon within the foraging range of Southern Resident Killer Whales in the next five to ten years?
                 </span>
                </p>
                <p class="font_8">
                </p>
                <p class="font_8">
                 Simply put, on average since the information concerning SRKW population decline was presented to the “God Squad” in 1999, we have wasted twenty of the twenty-five years of reproductive life potential of a typical southern resident killer whale while conducting additional “research” and ineffective and costly mitigation efforts for them and their primary prey (Chinook salmon). The situation as it stands requires at least the next five years to realize any possible benefit to salmon biomass from either hatchery supplementation or serious efforts to recover wild populations for the benefit of the whales (and for fishermen). The time to do something effective is now. The whales’ survival cannot wait for a Task Force report in November followed by executive action and more meetings in 2019.
                 <span style="text-decoration:underline;">
                 </span>
                </p>
               </div>

             <div class="txtNew" data-packed="true" id="comp-jhxtw0gm" style="top:1586px;bottom:;left:672px;right:;width:278px;height:auto;position:absolute;margin-left:calc((100% - 980px) * 0.5)">
              <h1 class="font_0" style="font-size:14px;">
               <span style="font-size:14px;">
                <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                 <span class="color_24">
                  News Release:
                 </span>
                </span>
               </span>
              </h1>
              <h1 class="font_0" style="font-size:14px;">
               <span style="font-size:14px;">
                <a data-content="http://www.pac.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/fm-gp/maps-cartes/salmon-saumon/2018-skrw-ers-eng.html" data-type="external" href="http://www.pac.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/fm-gp/maps-cartes/salmon-saumon/2018-skrw-ers-eng.html" rel="undefined" target="_blank">
                 <span class="color_24">
                  <span style="text-decoration:underline;">
                   Fisheries and Oceans Canada
                  </span>
                 </span>
                </a>
               </span>
              </h1>
              <h1 class="font_0" style="font-size:14px;">
               <span style="font-size:14px;">
                <a data-content="http://www.pac.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/fm-gp/maps-cartes/salmon-saumon/2018-skrw-ers-eng.html" data-type="external" href="http://www.pac.dfo-mpo.gc.ca/fm-gp/maps-cartes/salmon-saumon/2018-skrw-ers-eng.html" rel="undefined" target="_blank">
                 <span class="color_24">
                  <span style="text-decoration:underline;">
                   June 1, 2018
                  </span>
                 </span>
                </a>
               </span>
              </h1>
              <h1 class="font_0" style="font-size:14px;">
              </h1>
              <h1 class="font_0" style="font-size:16px;">
               <span class="color_14">
                <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                 <span style="font-size:16px;">
                  "Fisheries management measures to protect Southern Resident Killer Whales
                 </span>
                </span>
               </span>
              </h1>
              <p class="font_8">
               The seasonal distribution and movement patterns of Southern Resident killer whales are strongly associated with the availability of their preferred prey, Chinook salmon.
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
               Wild populations of Chinook salmon have declined dramatically in recent years. This lack of prey has been a critical factor in the decline of Southern Resident killer whales. To address this, the Government of Canada is imposing fishery management measures to reduce the total harvest for Chinook salmon by 25-35 percent. These measures include closures that will help increase the availability of this critical food source for Southern Resident killer whales.
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
               The closures will take place in three key foraging (feeding) areas: Strait of Juan de Fuca, Gulf Islands and the mouth of the Fraser River.
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
               These measures will be implemented for the 2018 salmon fishing season, with monitoring to assess the effectiveness of the closures."
              </p>
             </div>

             <div class="txtNew" data-packed="true" id="comp-jg6ooxlg" style="top:3029px;bottom:;left:462px;right:;width:489px;height:auto;position:absolute;margin-left:calc((100% - 980px) * 0.5)">
              <h6 class="font_6" style="line-height:1.4em;">
               <span class="color_13">
                Abstract
               </span>
              </h6>
              <p class="font_8" style="line-height:1.4em;">
               There are genetic risks associated with small population sizes, including loss of genetic diversity and inbreeding depression. The southern resident killer whale Orcinus orca population is a group of ~80 whales listed as ‘endangered’ under the U.S. Endangered Species Act. Recovery efforts are focused on increasing prey and reducing impacts from environmental disturbance, but the population’s small size and insularity suggest that inbreeding depression could also be important. We analyzed genotypes at 68–94 nuclear loci from 105 individuals to refine a population pedigree to evaluate inbreeding and the relationship between multi-locus heterozy-gosity and ﬁtness. Our results expand upon an earlier study and shed new light on both inbreeding within this population and the mating patterns of killer whales. We found that only two adult males sired 52% of the sampled progeny born since 1990.
              </p>
             </div>

               <div class="wp2img" data-style="" id="comp-jfbgixyeimg">
                <img alt="" data-type="image" id="comp-jfbgixyeimgimage"/>

             <style data-styleid="wp2" type="text/css">
              .wp2_zoomedin {cursor:url(https://static.parastorage.com/services/skins/2.1229.80/images/wysiwyg/core/themes/base/cursor_zoom_out.png), url(https://static.parastorage.com/services/skins/2.1229.80/images/wysiwyg/core/themes/base/cursor_zoom_out.cur), auto;overflow:hidden;display:block;}

             <div class="txtNew" data-packed="true" id="comp-jfbgfo6t" style="top:3574px;bottom:;left:330px;right:;width:619px;height:auto;position:absolute;margin-left:calc((100% - 980px) * 0.5)">
              <p class="font_8">
               <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                Ken Balcomb wrote the blog
                <a href="https://www.whaleresearch.com/blog" target="_self">
                 <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                  <span class="color_24">
                   <span style="text-decoration:underline;">
                    Home on the Range / Where the Southern Resident killer whales roam and forage
                   </span>
                  </span>
                 </span>
                </a>
                in response to the misconception that the Southern Resident killer whales (SRKW) are “resident” to only the Salish Sea area, where they are seen most frequently by humans.
               </span>
              </p>
              <p class="font_7" style="font-size:18px;">
              </p>
              <h6 class="font_6">
               Home on the Range / Where the Southern Resident killer whales roam and forage
              </h6>
              <p class="font_7" style="font-size:18px;">
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
               "It is naive to think that the Southern Resident killer whales  – J, K, and L pods – are only “resident” to the inland Salish Sea and that they depend primarily on Fraser River Chinook salmon stocks for their survival. The SRKWs spent 86-95% (varies by pod and matriline) of the total days in 2017 outside of Salish Sea waters ...
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
               <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                One thing is for sure:
               </span>
               The survival of the Southern Resident orcas will not wait for more United States and Canadian government meetings and scientific reports. Too much money has already been spent and is still being wasted. The salmon lost in years past should be evidence enough to convince decision makers that specific
               <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                action needs addressing immediately.
               </span>
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
              </p>
              <p class="font_8">
               <a href="https://www.whaleresearch.com/blog" target="_self">
                <span style="font-family:avenir-lt-w01_85-heavy1475544,sans-serif;">
                 <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                  <span class="color_24">
                   <span style="text-decoration:underline;">
                    Read full blog »
                   </span>
                  </span>
                 </span>
                </span>
               </a>
              </p>
             </div>

             <div class="txtNew" data-packed="true" id="comp-jfbdklge" style="top:4074px;bottom:;left:495px;right:;width:460px;height:auto;position:absolute;margin-left:calc((100% - 980px) * 0.5)">
              <p class="font_8" style="line-height:1.5em;">
               <span style="font-family:avenir-lt-w01_35-light1475496,sans-serif;">
                For over four decades, the Center for Whale Research has been conducting annual photo-ID (photo-identification) studies,
                <a href="https://www.whaleresearch.com/orcasurvey" target="_self">
                 <span class="color_24">
                  <span style="text-decoration:underline;">
                   Orca Survey
                  </span>
                 </span>
                </a>
                ,  of Southern Resident killer whales – one of the most magnificent and beloved animal populations in the world. Our long-term research has generated unprecedented baseline information on the whales’ population dynamics, health, demography, social structure, and individual life histories. Thanks to the Center’s research, more detail is known about the endangered Southern Resident killer whales than any other group of marine mammals in the world.  As a non-profit 501(c) 3 organization, our mission is to facilitate the recovery of this beloved population of Orcas through non-invasive scientific study, public awareness and education, and conservation action.
               </span>
               <span style="text-decoration:underline;">
                <a href="https://www.whaleresearch.com/donate" target="_self">
                 <span style="font-family:avenir-lt-w01_85-heavy1475544,sans-serif;">
                  <span style="font-weight:bold;">
                   Please support our important work today!
                  </span>
                 </span>
                </a>
               </span>
              </p>
             </div>

<\/span>– J, K, and L pods – are only “resident” to the inland Salish Sea and that they depend primarily on Fraser River Chinook salmon stocks for their survival.<\/hatul><hatul >The <span >SRKWs<\/span> spent 86-95% (varies by pod and matriline) of the total days in 2017 outside&nbsp;of Salish Sea waters.<\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Where were they, what were they eating?<\/span><\/hatul><hatul >We know from Dr. Brad Hanson’s <a dataquery=\"#txtMedia1klq\"><span >NOAA Fisheries satellite tagging studies<\/span><\/a>&nbsp;a few years ago that L pod-tagged orcas spent a high proportion of time (when the tags were functioning) in the region of the Columbia River entrance. Hanson also collected Chinook salmon scales and DNA in whale feces in this area in the trail of the whales.<\/hatul><hatul >There has long been evidence that the Southern Residents travel up and down the west coast, as well as in and out of the <a dataquery=\"#txtMediapqc\"><span >Salish Sea<\/span><\/a><span >,<\/span> “cherry picking” the <a dataquery=\"#txtMediarv2\"><span >Chinook salmon<\/span><\/a><span >,<\/span> but never staying in just one location (e.g., at a major river mouth gorging on all of the fish). In my experience, the orcas travel with pulses of inbound <a dataquery=\"#txtMedia1zlt\"><span >spawners<\/span><\/a>&nbsp;from coastal waters, through the Strait of Juan de Fuca and Haro Strait to Georgia Strait, then turn around and head back to or toward coastal waters. While inland, the whales travel at an average speed of 3.75 knots and cover about 75-90 miles per day, in relaxed foraging, mostly during incoming tides when the fish are moving toward the Fraser River mouth. They are always moving. However, as the biomass of Chinook per square mile diminishes, the whales spread out in smaller groups and appear more “busy” - attending to foraging rather than entertaining whale watchers. As a result of the Chinook fishery collapse in the inland region, the Southern Residents come into the Salish Sea much less often these days.<\/hatul><hatul >In the 1970s, the three pods that Dr. Mike Bigg identified in southern British Columbia waters were named J, K, and L (A-I pods were in northern BC waters), and they were discrete and separate enough for us to discern slightly different patterns in their distribution and association. J pod was encountered in Salish Sea waters in all months of the year and made forays into Puget Sound once or twice each month. The “Js” frequented Haro Strait; they passed through the strait every day or two from May through September when the <a dataquery=\"#txtMedia1f9l\"><span >seiners<\/span><\/a>&nbsp;were fishing daily. From the seiners, we obtained a pretty good idea of how many salmon were heading toward the Fraser River, and from the test sets, we had an index of how many fish got to the river. It took us awhile, and much scale sampling in trail of the whales to figure out that they were targeting Chinook, even during runs of millions of Sockeye and Pink salmon. The scat sampling and the molecular data show the same pattern.<\/hatul><hatul >During big runs of Chinook salmon, K and L pods joined J pod in the interior waters, and in the late 70s and early 80s spent much of the May through September season going back and forth from coastal waters to the Fraser plume. We know for a fact they went as far out in the Strait of Juan de Fuca as Swiftsure and La Perouse Banks because a colleague, Brian Gisborne, photographed them out there whenever they were not with us in interior waters.<\/hatul><hatul >During a five-year period from October 2007 through May 2012, I posted more than 6,000 “wanted” posters in eastern North Pacific coastal marinas, on telephone poles, and in seaside business locations, soliciting sighting reports of killer whales and photographs of them. I received 7,217 sighting reports and analyzed them for SRKW pod identification. I followed up on fresh reports and “dead reckoned” the whales at 75 miles per day to position myself ahead of their travels, where I went to sea to photograph the whales.<\/hatul><hatul >The winter distribution (i.e., November through April) of all SRKW pods was preponderantly coastal from Washington State to central California, although J pod conducted occasional forays into the Salish Sea and Puget Sound in winter months. They have not been documented south of Newport, Oregon. My ID experts and I identified as many individual whales as possible in each sighting event and summed “whale days” spent in a broad coastal area (by state). A “whale day” was defined as one identified whale in a specific area, including the days required to travel to and through the area; and, if it was reasonable surmise to include additional whales were present, the additional whales were included (e.g., a matriline composed of five whales = five whale days). The results schematically were:<\/hatul><hatul style=\"text-align: center; \" ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><span style=\"\">&nbsp;Marine Mammal Science Note - SRKWWinter Distribution 20130209<\/span><\/span><\/hatul><hatul style=\"\" ><span style=\"\"><span >There is no evidence to the contrary, either historical or as a result of the present studies, that indicates SRKW's might have a significant offshore distribution at times when they are not in inland marine waters. Thus far, the evidence for SRKW distribution in Canadian waters is consistent with this conclusion, but remains to be analyzed and reported (J. Ford, pers. Comm.). This continental shelf distribution should come as no surprise - the ocean productivity for these whales and their prey species is preponderantly coastal and inshore in the eastern North Pacific ocean (see SEAWIFS, NOAA).<\/span><\/span><\/hatul><hatul >The satellite tagging studies of SRKW by Dr. Hanson showed much the same travel pattern&nbsp;and illuminated the model for winter months. L pod was most coastal in distribution, spending much time off Washington State, particularly in and north of the Columbia River plume; but, occasionally traveling for a week or so down to central California (Sacramento River\/San Joaquin River Chinook salmon runs). K pod sometimes went with them, but in general seemed to range intermediate between L and J pods.<\/hatul><hatul >Because the SRKW must eat the equivalent of about 2.5% - 5% of their body weight pretty much daily, the coastal waters were and are important foraging areas for all three pods. In total, they probably eat as many as 580,000 twenty-pound Chinook salmon per year. I am sure that we could calculate the Salish Sea Chinook salmon contribution to the SRKW’s diet. The rest of their “catch” is coastal.<\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">What is the take-home message from all of this?<\/span><\/hatul><hatul >The Southern Resident killer whales go where the Chinook are, looking for the energy-rich big ones. From the whales’ point of view, confirmed by distribution and foraging studies, the <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a dataquery=\"#txtMedia13ts\"><span >Columbia\/Snake River Chinook salmon<\/span><\/a><\/span>&nbsp;contribution is vital. We know from photographs taken as recently as last month that L pod was off Ocean Shores, WA.<\/hatul><hatul >It is just not reasonable to think that Columbia\/Snake River salmon are not of importance to the Southern Resident killer whales. If the Snake River became a big, wild Chinook producer again, it would be an enormous benefit for the SRKW community. The Washington and Oregon coastal waters were proven to be recurrent distribution areas for the SRKWs during the study period cited above and are even more critical now that the Fraser River Chinook have collapsed.<\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">One thing is for sure:<\/span> The survival of the Southern Resident orcas will not wait for more United States and Canadian government meetings and scientific reports. Too much money has already been spent and is still&nbsp;being wasted. The salmon lost in years past should be evidence enough to convince decision makers that <span style=\"font-style:italic;\">specific action needs addressing immediately.<\/span><\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><\/span>Photograph by&nbsp;Joey Winkler @weareanthro, anthro Films.<\/hatul><hatul ><br>\n&nbsp;<\/hatul>","links":[{"linkId":"txtMediaa2i","_type":"wix:PageLink","pageId":"sqlbx"},{"linkId":"txtMedia1tsk","_type":"wix:PageLink","pageId":"cto2"},{"linkId":"txtMedia1klq","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"www.nwfsc.noaa.gov\/research\/divisions\/cb\/ecosystem\/marinemammal\/satellite_tagging\/index.cfm"},{"linkId":"txtMediapqc","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"georgiastrait.org\/issues\/about-the-strait-2\/the-salish-sea\/"},{"linkId":"txtMediarv2","_type":"wix:PageLink","pageId":"cjla"},{"linkId":"txtMedia1zlt","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"salmonfactswork.weebly.com\/spawner.html"},{"linkId":"txtMedia1f9l","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Seine_fishing"},{"linkId":"txtMedia13ts","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"damsense.org\/southern-resident-orcas\/"}],"version":3},"coverImageData":{"_type":"CoverImageData","coverImageType":"photo","video":{"_type":"wix:Video","videoId":"","videoType":"","thumbnail":""},"photo":{"_type":"wix:Image","title":"","src":"760f65_8d0b029e0e7a4cb38600b950f7aaa70b~mv2.jpg","width":800,"height":1067},"isHD":false,"isHeroImage":false},"description":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"","links":[],"version":1},"mobileTitle":"Home on the long does it take for a dorsal fin to straighten?","date":{"_type":"wix:Date","iso":"2018-02-28T23:42:46.017Z"},"text":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"<hatul >When a killer whale calf is born, it's&nbsp;dorsal fin is bent over. When we first saw J49, in August 2012, it's fin was bent. We wondered how long it would take for it to straighten. We found the answer to that question very quickly.&nbsp;<\/hatul><hatul >In this three minute video, Dave Ellifrit takes us through the first few months of a killer whale calf's development, from \"tiny little wrinkly, pencilly thin sorta thing\" to scaly skin&nbsp;and then to a plump and yellowish little whale. Very interesting and lots of fun to watch.&nbsp;<\/hatul><hatul >This video is an excerpt from Dave's presentation on July 21, 2017, at CWR's Celebrating Science workshop.<\/hatul>","links":[],"version":3},"coverImageData":{"_type":"CoverImageData","coverImageType":"video","video":{"_type":"wix:Video","videoId":"mAfWezb7rbc","videoType":"YOUTUBE","thumbnail":"\/\/img.youtube.com\/vi\/mAfWezb7rbc\/mqdefault.jpg","imageSrc":"\/\/img.youtube.com\/vi\/mAfWezb7rbc\/0.jpg"},"photo":{"_type":"wix:Image","title":"","src":"","width":1280,"height":960},"isHD":false,"isHeroImage":false},"description":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"","links":[],"version":1},"mobileTitle":"How long does it take for a dorsal fin to straighten?","_iid":"5a9736f39890cc468c998f41","_hash":"5597757354aab76b882a0091eaf738ea","_createdAt":"2018-02-28T23:10:43.092Z","_updatedAt":"2018-03-01T00:26:32.509Z","permalink":"2018\/02\/28\/How-long-does-it-take-for-a-dorsal-fin-to-straighten","permalinkVersion":"2","defaultPost":false,"author":"","categories":[]},"5a707c22e6ac717e90384c58":{"_type":"MediaPost","title":"Finding Acceptance","date":{"_type":"wix:Date","iso":"2018-01-30T14:16:55.287Z"},"text":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"<hatul >The second in a series of video excerpts from our Celebrating Science workshop held on July 21, 2017, on San Juan Island. Dr. Astrid van Ginneken - Finding Acceptance<\/hatul>","links":[],"version":3},"coverImageData":{"_type":"CoverImageData","coverImageType":"video","video":{"_type":"wix:Video","videoId":"wUz-F2eNkXg","videoType":"YOUTUBE","thumbnail":"\/\/img.youtube.com\/vi\/wUz-F2eNkXg\/mqdefault.jpg","imageSrc":"\/\/img.youtube.com\/vi\/wUz-F2eNkXg\/0.jpg"},"photo":{"_type":"wix:Image","title":"","src":"","width":1280,"height":960},"isHD":false,"isHeroImage":false},"defaultPost":false,"_iid":"5a707c22e6ac717e90384c58","_hash":"45116ad8d6a9d0c0a3c4b3bda72b2d53","_createdAt":"2018-01-30T14:07:30.460Z","_updatedAt":"2018-03-01T00:29:20.185Z","permalink":"2018\/01\/30\/Finding-Acceptance","permalinkVersion":"2","description":{"_type":"wix:RichText","links":[],"version":3,"text":""},"mobileTitle":"Finding Acceptance","author":"","categories":[]}},"converted":{"Posts":{"5ab55e036f8a3e4377f67570":{"_type":"PhotoPost","title":"Home on the Range","date":{"_type":"wix:Date","iso":"2018-03-24T20:10:58.132Z"},"text":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"<hatul ><a dataquery=\"#txtMediaa2i\"><span >Ken Balcomb<\/span><\/a><span >, Center for Whale Research founder and senior scientist, responding to the misconception that the Southern Resident killer whales (SRKW) are “resident” to the Salish Sea area, where they are seen most frequently by humans.<\/span>&nbsp;<\/hatul><hatul style=\"\" ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><span style=\"\">Home on the Range<\/span><\/span><\/hatul><hatul style=\"\" ><span style=\"\">Where the Southern Resident killer whales roam and forage<\/span><\/hatul><hatul >It is naive to think that the <a dataquery=\"#txtMedia1tsk\"><span >Southern Resident killer whales<\/span><\/a><span style=\"\">&nbsp; <\/span>– J, K, and L pods – are only “resident” to the inland Salish Sea and that they depend primarily on Fraser River Chinook salmon stocks for their survival.<\/hatul><hatul >The <span >SRKWs<\/span> spent 86-95% (varies by pod and matriline) of the total days in 2017 outside&nbsp;of Salish Sea waters.<\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">Where were they, what were they eating?<\/span><\/hatul><hatul >We know from Dr. Brad Hanson’s <a dataquery=\"#txtMedia1klq\"><span >NOAA Fisheries satellite tagging studies<\/span><\/a>&nbsp;a few years ago that L pod-tagged orcas spent a high proportion of time (when the tags were functioning) in the region of the Columbia River entrance. Hanson also collected Chinook salmon scales and DNA in whale feces in this area in the trail of the whales.<\/hatul><hatul >There has long been evidence that the Southern Residents travel up and down the west coast, as well as in and out of the <a dataquery=\"#txtMediapqc\"><span >Salish Sea<\/span><\/a><span >,<\/span> “cherry picking” the <a dataquery=\"#txtMediarv2\"><span >Chinook salmon<\/span><\/a><span >,<\/span> but never staying in just one location (e.g., at a major river mouth gorging on all of the fish). In my experience, the orcas travel with pulses of inbound <a dataquery=\"#txtMedia1zlt\"><span >spawners<\/span><\/a>&nbsp;from coastal waters, through the Strait of Juan de Fuca and Haro Strait to Georgia Strait, then turn around and head back to or toward coastal waters. While inland, the whales travel at an average speed of 3.75 knots and cover about 75-90 miles per day, in relaxed foraging, mostly during incoming tides when the fish are moving toward the Fraser River mouth. They are always moving. However, as the biomass of Chinook per square mile diminishes, the whales spread out in smaller groups and appear more “busy” - attending to foraging rather than entertaining whale watchers. As a result of the Chinook fishery collapse in the inland region, the Southern Residents come into the Salish Sea much less often these days.<\/hatul><hatul >In the 1970s, the three pods that Dr. Mike Bigg identified in southern British Columbia waters were named J, K, and L (A-I pods were in northern BC waters), and they were discrete and separate enough for us to discern slightly different patterns in their distribution and association. J pod was encountered in Salish Sea waters in all months of the year and made forays into Puget Sound once or twice each month. The “Js” frequented Haro Strait; they passed through the strait every day or two from May through September when the <a dataquery=\"#txtMedia1f9l\"><span >seiners<\/span><\/a>&nbsp;were fishing daily. From the seiners, we obtained a pretty good idea of how many salmon were heading toward the Fraser River, and from the test sets, we had an index of how many fish got to the river. It took us awhile, and much scale sampling in trail of the whales to figure out that they were targeting Chinook, even during runs of millions of Sockeye and Pink salmon. The scat sampling and the molecular data show the same pattern.<\/hatul><hatul >During big runs of Chinook salmon, K and L pods joined J pod in the interior waters, and in the late 70s and early 80s spent much of the May through September season going back and forth from coastal waters to the Fraser plume. We know for a fact they went as far out in the Strait of Juan de Fuca as Swiftsure and La Perouse Banks because a colleague, Brian Gisborne, photographed them out there whenever they were not with us in interior waters.<\/hatul><hatul >During a five-year period from October 2007 through May 2012, I posted more than 6,000 “wanted” posters in eastern North Pacific coastal marinas, on telephone poles, and in seaside business locations, soliciting sighting reports of killer whales and photographs of them. I received 7,217 sighting reports and analyzed them for SRKW pod identification. I followed up on fresh reports and “dead reckoned” the whales at 75 miles per day to position myself ahead of their travels, where I went to sea to photograph the whales.<\/hatul><hatul >The winter distribution (i.e., November through April) of all SRKW pods was preponderantly coastal from Washington State to central California, although J pod conducted occasional forays into the Salish Sea and Puget Sound in winter months. They have not been documented south of Newport, Oregon. My ID experts and I identified as many individual whales as possible in each sighting event and summed “whale days” spent in a broad coastal area (by state). A “whale day” was defined as one identified whale in a specific area, including the days required to travel to and through the area; and, if it was reasonable surmise to include additional whales were present, the additional whales were included (e.g., a matriline composed of five whales = five whale days). The results schematically were:<\/hatul><hatul style=\"text-align: center; \" ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><span style=\"\">&nbsp;Marine Mammal Science Note - SRKWWinter Distribution 20130209<\/span><\/span><\/hatul><hatul style=\"\" ><span style=\"\"><span >There is no evidence to the contrary, either historical or as a result of the present studies, that indicates SRKW's might have a significant offshore distribution at times when they are not in inland marine waters. Thus far, the evidence for SRKW distribution in Canadian waters is consistent with this conclusion, but remains to be analyzed and reported (J. Ford, pers. Comm.). This continental shelf distribution should come as no surprise - the ocean productivity for these whales and their prey species is preponderantly coastal and inshore in the eastern North Pacific ocean (see SEAWIFS, NOAA).<\/span><\/span><\/hatul><hatul >The satellite tagging studies of SRKW by Dr. Hanson showed much the same travel pattern&nbsp;and illuminated the model for winter months. L pod was most coastal in distribution, spending much time off Washington State, particularly in and north of the Columbia River plume; but, occasionally traveling for a week or so down to central California (Sacramento River\/San Joaquin River Chinook salmon runs). K pod sometimes went with them, but in general seemed to range intermediate between L and J pods.<\/hatul><hatul >Because the SRKW must eat the equivalent of about 2.5% - 5% of their body weight pretty much daily, the coastal waters were and are important foraging areas for all three pods. In total, they probably eat as many as 580,000 twenty-pound Chinook salmon per year. I am sure that we could calculate the Salish Sea Chinook salmon contribution to the SRKW’s diet. The rest of their “catch” is coastal.<\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">What is the take-home message from all of this?<\/span><\/hatul><hatul >The Southern Resident killer whales go where the Chinook are, looking for the energy-rich big ones. From the whales’ point of view, confirmed by distribution and foraging studies, the <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\"><a dataquery=\"#txtMedia13ts\"><span >Columbia\/Snake River Chinook salmon<\/span><\/a><\/span>&nbsp;contribution is vital. We know from photographs taken as recently as last month that L pod was off Ocean Shores, WA.<\/hatul><hatul >It is just not reasonable to think that Columbia\/Snake River salmon are not of importance to the Southern Resident killer whales. If the Snake River became a big, wild Chinook producer again, it would be an enormous benefit for the SRKW community. The Washington and Oregon coastal waters were proven to be recurrent distribution areas for the SRKWs during the study period cited above and are even more critical now that the Fraser River Chinook have collapsed.<\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\">One thing is for sure:<\/span> The survival of the Southern Resident orcas will not wait for more United States and Canadian government meetings and scientific reports. Too much money has already been spent and is still&nbsp;being wasted. The salmon lost in years past should be evidence enough to convince decision makers that <span style=\"font-style:italic;\">specific action needs addressing immediately.<\/span><\/hatul><hatul ><span style=\"font-weight:bold;\"><\/span>Photograph by&nbsp;Joey Winkler @weareanthro, anthro Films.<\/hatul><hatul ><br>\n&nbsp;<\/hatul>","links":[{"linkId":"txtMediaa2i","_type":"wix:PageLink","pageId":"sqlbx"},{"linkId":"txtMedia1tsk","_type":"wix:PageLink","pageId":"cto2"},{"linkId":"txtMedia1klq","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"www.nwfsc.noaa.gov\/research\/divisions\/cb\/ecosystem\/marinemammal\/satellite_tagging\/index.cfm"},{"linkId":"txtMediapqc","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"georgiastrait.org\/issues\/about-the-strait-2\/the-salish-sea\/"},{"linkId":"txtMediarv2","_type":"wix:PageLink","pageId":"cjla"},{"linkId":"txtMedia1zlt","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"salmonfactswork.weebly.com\/spawner.html"},{"linkId":"txtMedia1f9l","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Seine_fishing"},{"linkId":"txtMedia13ts","_type":"wix:ExternalLink","target":"_blank","protocol":"https","address":"damsense.org\/southern-resident-orcas\/"}],"version":3},"coverImageData":{"_type":"CoverImageData","coverImageType":"photo","video":{"_type":"wix:Video","videoId":"","videoType":"","thumbnail":""},"photo":{"_type":"wix:Image","title":"","src":"760f65_8d0b029e0e7a4cb38600b950f7aaa70b~mv2.jpg","width":800,"height":1067},"isHD":false,"isHeroImage":false},"description":{"_type":"wix:RichText","text":"","links":[],"version":1},"mobileTitle":"Home style=\"font-size:18px\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<h6 class=\"font_6\">Home on the Range \/ Where the Southern Resident killer whales roam and forage<\/h6>\n\n<p class=\"font_7\" style=\"font-size:18px\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">&quot;It is naive to think that the Southern Resident killer whales&nbsp; &ndash; J, K, and L pods &ndash; are only &ldquo;resident&rdquo; to the inland Salish Sea and that they depend primarily on Fraser River Chinook salmon stocks for their survival. The southern resident killer whale Orcinus orca population is a group of ~80 whales listed as &lsquo;endangered&rsquo; under the U.S. Endangered Species Act. Recovery efforts are focused on increasing prey and reducing impacts from environmental disturbance, but the population&rsquo;s small size and insularity suggest that inbreeding depression could also be important. style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><a dataquery=\"#textLink_jhxu5zk0\"><span class=\"color_24\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Fisheries and Oceans Canada<\/span><\/span><\/a><\/span><\/h1>\n\n<h1 class=\"font_0\" style=\"font-size:14px\"><span style=\"font-size:14px\"><a dataquery=\"#textLink_jhxu5zk0\"><span class=\"color_24\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">June 1, 2018<\/span><\/span><\/a><\/span><\/h1>\n\n<h1 class=\"font_0\" style=\"font-size:14px\">&nbsp;<\/h1>\n\n<h1 class=\"font_0\" style=\"font-size:16px\"><span class=\"color_14\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">&quot;Fisheries management measures to protect Southern Resident Killer Whales<\/span><\/span><\/span><\/h1>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">The seasonal distribution and movement patterns of Southern Resident killer whales are strongly associated with the availability of their preferred prey, Chinook salmon.<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">Wild populations of Chinook salmon have declined dramatically in recent years. This lack of prey has been a critical factor in the decline of Southern Resident killer whales. To address this, the Government of Canada is imposing fishery management measures to reduce the total harvest for Chinook salmon by 25-35 percent. These measures include closures that will help increase the availability of this critical food source for Southern Resident killer whales.<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">The closures will take place in three key foraging (feeding) areas: Strait of Juan de Fuca, Gulf Islands and the mouth of the Fraser River.<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">These measures will be implemented for the 2018 salmon fishing season, with monitoring to assess the effectiveness of the closures.&quot;<\/p>","stylesMapId":"CK_EDITOR_PARAGRAPH_STYLES","linkList":["#textLink_jhxu5zk0"]},"dataItem-jihjgp1h":{"type":"Image","id":"dataItem-jihjgp1h","metaData":{"isPreset":false,"schemaVersion":"2.0","isHidden":false},"title":"","uri":"760f65_f981d95a2b9e48c698dbadeab77c3968~mv2.jpg","description":"","width":1203,"height":803,"alt":""},"dataItem-jihjhzz4":{"type":"StyledText","id":"dataItem-jihjhzz4","metaData":{"isPreset":false,"schemaVersion":"1.0","isHidden":false},"text":"<p class=\"font_8\" style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><span style=\"font-family:avenir-lt-w01_35-light1475496,sans-serif;\"><span class=\"color_14\">Press Release &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;June 16, 2018<\/span><\/span><\/span><\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\"><span class=\"color_14\"><span style=\"font-family:raleway,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:24px\">L92 - Missing Southern Resident killer whale is presumed dead<\/span><\/span><\/span><\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">On Monday, June 11, more than 50 Southern Resident killer whales returned to inland waters, including J pod, L87, and most but not all of L pod. It has been nearly 2 months since J pod whales and L87 have been seen in local waters, an unusually long break but not unexpected based on trends in the past decade. In recent years, encounter data and sighting data compiled by the Center for Research show that the Southern Residents have been spending fewer days in inland waters in the April-May time frame. This trend parallels a decline in the abundance of the Fraser River spring Chinook salmon runs.<\/p>","stylesMapId":"CK_EDITOR_PARAGRAPH_STYLES","linkList":[]},"dataItem-jihjix1e":{"type":"LinkableButton","id":"dataItem-jihjix1e","metaData":{"isPreset":false,"schemaVersion":"1.0","isHidden":false},"label":"Read The southern resident killer whale Orcinus orca population is a group of ~80 whales listed as &lsquo;endangered&rsquo; under the U.S. Endangered Species Act. Recovery efforts are focused on increasing prey and reducing impacts from environmental disturbance, but the population&rsquo;s small size and insularity suggest that inbreeding depression could also be important. We analyzed genotypes at 68&ndash;94 nuclear loci from 105 individuals to refine a population pedigree to evaluate inbreeding and the relationship between multi-locus heterozy-gosity and ﬁtness. Our results expand upon an earlier study and shed new light on both inbreeding within this population and the mating patterns of killer whales. class=\"color_14\"><span style=\"font-weight:bold\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">&quot;Fisheries management measures to protect Southern Resident Killer Whales<\/span><\/span><\/span><\/h1>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">The seasonal distribution and movement patterns of Southern Resident killer whales are strongly associated with the availability of their preferred prey, Chinook salmon.<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">Wild populations of Chinook salmon have declined dramatically in recent years. This lack of prey has been a critical factor in the decline of Southern Resident killer whales. To address this, the Government of Canada is imposing fishery management measures to reduce the total harvest for Chinook salmon by 25-35 percent. These measures include closures that will help increase the availability of this critical food source for Southern Resident killer whales.<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">The closures will take place in three key foraging (feeding) areas: Strait of Juan de Fuca, Gulf Islands and the mouth of the Fraser River.<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">These measures will be implemented for the 2018 salmon fishing season, with monitoring to assess the effectiveness of the closures.&quot;<\/p>","stylesMapId":"CK_EDITOR_PARAGRAPH_STYLES","linkList":["#textLink_jhxu5zk0"]},"dataItem-jihjgp1h":{"type":"Image","id":"dataItem-jihjgp1h","metaData":{"isPreset":false,"schemaVersion":"2.0","isHidden":false},"title":"","uri":"760f65_f981d95a2b9e48c698dbadeab77c3968~mv2.jpg","description":"","width":1203,"height":803,"alt":""},"dataItem-jihjhzz4":{"type":"StyledText","id":"dataItem-jihjhzz4","metaData":{"isPreset":false,"schemaVersion":"1.0","isHidden":false},"text":"<p class=\"font_8\" style=\"font-size: 16px;\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;\"><span style=\"font-family:avenir-lt-w01_35-light1475496,sans-serif;\"><span class=\"color_14\">Press Release &ndash;&nbsp;&nbsp;June 16, 2018<\/span><\/span><\/span><\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\"><span class=\"color_14\"><span style=\"font-family:raleway,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:24px\">L92 - Missing Southern Resident killer whale is presumed dead<\/span><\/span><\/span><\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">&nbsp;<\/p>\n\n<p class=\"font_8\">On Monday, June 11, more than 50 Southern Resident killer whales returned to inland waters, including J pod, L87, and most but not all of L pod. It has been nearly 2 months since J pod whales and L87 have been seen in local waters, an unusually long break but not unexpected based on trends in the past decade. In recent years, encounter data and sighting data compiled by the Center for Research show that the Southern Residents have been spending fewer days in inland waters in the April-May time frame. This trend parallels a decline in the abundance of the Fraser River spring Chinook salmon
